<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,1338]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,371,257,282]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">
Notes on 
<typeStatus box="[309,371,257,282]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">types</typeStatus>
</emphasis>
. The “small supra-antennal spot” on the frons in the original description in Melander (
<number box="[1343,1401,257,282]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" value="1950.0">1950</number>
) is not a pigmented mark but a grease mark. The frons is completely yellow in the 
<typeStatus box="[1061,1163,292,317]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">holotype</typeStatus>
. The 
<typeStatus box="[1226,1324,292,317]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">holotype</typeStatus>
female is greasy on the wings and head, otherwise is in fair condition. There is a small tear at the base of the left wing and the right antennal segments beyond the pedicel have broken off and are missing.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="205" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,1338]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,431,398,423]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">Diagnostic features</emphasis>
. Face and frons yellow; postgena without posterior extension (
<figureCitation box="[1165,1232,398,423]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,249,1989,2011]" captionTargetBox="[156,1430,768,1958]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,758,1965]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Platypygus americanus holotype: a — lateral view, b — wing, c — dorsal view of mesonotum and abdomen." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/248550/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">
Fig. 
<number box="[1221,1232,399,423]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
a); occiput black; pronotum with small orange mark dorsomedially; mesonotum yellowish white with three longitudinal orange stripes, with moderately dense white hairs; scutellum yellowish white with white hairs; lateral margin of mesonotum yellowish white; spot next to transverse suture absent (
<figureCitation box="[931,998,503,528]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,249,1989,2011]" captionTargetBox="[156,1430,768,1958]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,758,1965]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Platypygus americanus holotype: a — lateral view, b — wing, c — dorsal view of mesonotum and abdomen." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/248550/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">
Fig. 
<number box="[986,998,504,528]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
c); pleura completely yellowish white without black mark; halter yellowish white; crossvein r-m at middle of cell dm (
<figureCitation box="[1089,1155,539,564]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,249,1989,2011]" captionTargetBox="[156,1430,768,1958]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,758,1965]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Platypygus americanus holotype: a — lateral view, b — wing, c — dorsal view of mesonotum and abdomen." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/248550/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">
Fig. 
<number box="[1144,1155,539,564]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
b); legs yellowish white except two last tarsal segments blackish; abdomen yellowish with short adpressed whitish hairs dorsally.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,1338]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,399,609,634]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">Female genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[418,490,609,634]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,249,1923,1945]" captionTargetBox="[239,1323,202,1868]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[227,1335,193,1881]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Platypygus americanus female genitalia. Abbreviations: c = canaliculi, s. r. = spermathecal reservoir, a. s. d. = apical spermathecal duct, b. s. d. = basal spermathecal duct, c. s. d. = common spermathecal duct, f. = furca, s. = sclerite adjacent to genital orifice." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/248551/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">
Fig. 
<number box="[474,490,610,634]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
). [Note: Hall &amp; Evenhuis (
<number box="[810,871,609,634]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" value="1986.0">1986</number>
: 
<number box="[885,928,610,634]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" value="328.0">328</number>
) illustrated the female genitalia but did not provide a description. We here give the first description of the female genitalia.] Furca U-shaped, sclerotized, lateral arms thin, birfurcate apically, connected by thickly sclerotized slightly bilobed bridge, with two small linear sclerites next to genital orifice; common spermathecal duct very short; each spermathecal duct divided into two sections, basal section, transversely striated, long, broad, apical section narrow and smooth duct, without distinct sperm pump or valves; basal part of median spermathecal duct narrower than that of lateral ducts, without striation, twisted spirally on basal half, thin, straight on distal half toward reservoir; lateral spermathecal ducts about 
<number box="[1354,1368,821,845]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" value="3.0">3</number>
times width of median duct; spermathecal reservoirs obovate, slightly indented medially, with short and dense canaliculi apica 
<number box="[212,240,891,916]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" value="64.0">64</number>
lly.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
